researches internet addiction

 

Just one more cigarette. Just one more
drink Just one more hit. Just one more link?
For some, travelling the Information
Superhighway may be more of a need than
a pleasure. Recent evidence has shown that
on-line abuse falls under the same clinical
classiﬁcation as substance addiction.

Kimberly Young, a clinical psycholo-
gist and assistant professor of psychology at
Pitt’s Bradford campus, is conducting
unprecedented research on the latest phe-
nomenon in the Infonnation Age: on-line
addiction.

Though she cites her research as
“exploratory and qualitative in nature,”
Young has attracted national attention for
her efforts to classify this rapidly growing
problem as a clinical impairment. .

Young said the psychological need to
spend time on the intemet is similar to an
alcoholic needing another drink or a smoker
experiencing a nicotine lit. The criteria for
determining clinical intemet addiction
closely resembles that for substances.

“I have modiﬁed this study so that the
internet is substituted for substances,” said
Young.

Young’s study focuses onpeoplelwho
spend an excessive amount of time using
interactive on-line applications including
chat rooms and multi—user dungeons, which
are intemet enclaves allowing people to
receive live feedback from one another.

As part of her study, Young released a
survey in an on-line interactive forum. Over
400 responses poured in from people who
claimed to spend too much time on-line.

The Autumn issue of the University of
Pittsburgh’s Research Review indicated
nearly 80 percent of the respondents ﬁt
Young’s deﬁnition of an addict. On average,
addicts spent 40 to 50 hours a week engaged
in some type of interactive intemet function

 

and suffered from diﬁerent levels of depen-
dence. ‘

Her research follows the criteria estab-
lishing addiction guidelines dictated in the
American Psychiatric Association’s’
Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of
Mental Disorders.

Young said symptoms include such
behaviors as staying on-line longer than
intended, developing a tolerance so that
more time must be spent on-line to achieve
a level of satisfaction, and experiencing
withdrawal symptoms otf-line. _

Young stated that college students are
one of the most vulnerable groups becoming
addicted to the intemet.

“They are often experiencing the ﬁrst
independence from their parents and many
times have difficulty acclimating to campus
life,” she said. “The intemet provides an out-
let for meeting people and hanging out.”

The problem with this type of social
interaction, according to Young, is that it
often encourages personality distortion as
well as isolation.

“The internet allows one to alter his or
her persona A shy person loses their inhibi-
tions and is easily able to express his or her-
self in ways that would seem too risky for
face-to-face communication,” says Young.

Young said people can become addict-
ed to the attention they are able to attract
with their false identities, allowing the inter-
net to consume more of their time and ener-
gy.

Young also considers calling in sick to
work, skipping school, and giving up recre-
ational and social activities to spend time on
the intemet signs of addiction.

As more researchers become involved
with the issue, Young remains a pioneer of
the study. She is planning to publish the ﬁrst
book on intemet addiction next winter.

Her overall prognosis for the problem is
bleak: “This is extremely serious,” she said.
“The snowball is just beginning.”

