Greyhound anywhere don’t leave me too many
options. I think the best medicine for me and for the
rest of us who are suffering from the dreadful “I’m
stuck in Oakland forever!” disease is to go camping,
somewhere South.

Camping is probably my favorite thing to do. I
can sleep late. I can go hiking and enjoy the fresh air.
I can have a campﬁre (the secret love of all closet
pyromaniacs). Most importantly, I can sit and think,
uninterrupted. No classes, no buildings, no semi-
breathable air, no horrible city tap water, no home-
work, no people being arrested in front of my house.
All these things contribute to a more peaceful state
of mind. '

Another option is to go camping with good
friends, which is often a necessity if you don’t own
a car. Camping is a great way to enjoy each other’s
company without having to wony about what time
you have class tomorrow or “Sony, I can’t talk right
now. I have work to do.” With camping, ﬁiends are
each other’s captive audience.

Sometimes though, it is not always possible to
get transportation to the camping resort of your
dreams. The best remedy for this ailment is to play
the pretend game. Invite some friends over. Clear
your living room of all its furniture. Next, set up a
tent in the middle of the room. Take some green see-
through plastic and cover the lights with it (not too
close or the pretend game will turn into a giant bon-
ﬁre). Play “’Ihe lion sleeps tonight” on the stereo and
roast marshmallows over the gas stove. My father
used to tell me to roast them over a ﬂashlight; I gave
up after the third day of waiting.

Some advice for those who do go camping over
spring break. First, there is no such thing as a snipe.

 

If someone asks you to catch one, tell them to draw -

you a picture. Second, there is no such thing as a left-
handed-smoke-shifter. If someone asks you to bor-
row one from the neighboring campers, don’t. What

I like to do is disappear for a half—hour and make a g

contraption/thing-a-rna-bob out of tin cans and vari-
ous other things which are stuck in the car. Then, I
come back with a smile on my face and say, “Sony,
all they had was a right-handed one.” It usually gets
a good laugh. Be creative.

Here are a list of things that are fun to do when
you go camping. First are the standards: canoeing,
rafting, hiking, ﬁshing, swimming, etc. These are all
a great deal of fun,but there area few other things to
do. Gambling and drinking (for those over 21 only,
of course) are a great way to spend an evening with
nothing better to do. Good friends, a deck of cards,
good beer, and clean fresh air, who could ask for

‘anything more? (Toyota perhaps.) If you are

opposed to gambling, use poker chips. While it may
seem a bit childish, I doubt I can ﬁnd anyone in col-
lege who wouldn’t like a good night game of hide
and seek, capture the ﬂag, or ﬂashlight tag. And
besides, I wouldn’t put anything past drunken col-
lege students. For those of us who have been known
to play football on the Cathedral lawn at two in the
morning, these games don’t seem like much of a
stretch.

But seriously, what I like most about camping
are the hikes I take alone. Solitude in a beautiful
woodland setting is extremely cahning. If any of you
go camping with friends this spring break, I urge you
to take some time to appreciate our vanishing nature.
Take time to marvel at the beauty of things that are
not man made. Mankind has done some amazing
things in history, but it has not and probably wﬂl
never surpass the amazing accomplishments of time
and evolution. It helps one realize how small and
insigniﬁcant man is in the history and vast expanse
of the universe. Pay particular attention to the stars.
With the light pollution and dismal weather, it is hard
to see many around here, but out in the country they
are amazing.

I know most of you do not share my fascination
with roughing it, but anyone can rent a cabin and do
the same thing. It is truly worth it. It makes us appre-
ciate the convenience of the technological innova-
tions that pervade our city life.

Jay DeMar1ino wishes that he still had the time to go
camping once a month.

