There's something funny

about all this technology

 

Technology. What is it good for?
Absolutely nothing. Okay, bad joke, but
an important topic. According to the
media and all of the ads by the major
intemet providers and computer compa-
nies on television, we are living’ in a
glorious age where technological
advances are making the world a better
place to live every day. Is this true? Not
entirely.

Please don’t think that I am a
technophobe. I enjoy new technology
just like everyone else, particularly the
intemet. But for all of the good things
that have resulted from our movement
into the Information Age, there -have
been a number of unfortunate side
effects that I think we would be foolish
to ignore. In addition to being a forum
for ideas, the intemet has also become a
lair where people can freely distribute
X—Files—type conspiracy theories and
hate groups can disseminate their lies to

people who might not know better.

Also, the intemet is not about inforrna—
tion. It is about marketing. In 1996,
some 40,000 companies had web sites
on the intemet, and that number has
been increasing exponentially.
Technology can be a great gift, but it
can be a curse as well.

Last December, I was fascinated by
an article in USA Today by economist
Paul Krugman, whose writings have
greatly inﬂuenced my thinking.
Krugman mocked the conventional wis-
dom that we are living in an age of
amazing progress by pointing out that
technology has not lived up to its
promises. Krugman noted that, accord-
ing to the ﬁlm 2001, in just four more
years technology will enable us to take
trips into space, and there would be
“computers smart enough to go on a
postal-worker-style rampage when they
feel unappreciated.” Krugman went on
to observe another example of how
computers haven’t lived up to their
hype: in 1958, a noted computer pio-
neer claimed that by the year 1970, a
computer would be the world chess
champion. That has yet to happen, and I
doubt that it will any time in the future.
If a computer specifically designed to
play chess cannot outwit a human, then
how can it solve the problems of the
world?

. Speaker of the House Newt
Gingrich is a well known technophile
who sees technology as the answer to
many of our problems. Gingrich is an
admirer of the works of Alvin Tofﬂer, a
futurist who believes that the world is
moving from an industry-based society
into an information-based society.

Gingrich frequently invokes Tofﬂer’s
pro—technology, pro—decentralization
themes in his speeches (but he does
neglect to mention that Tofﬂer has criti-
cized the Republicans for not trying to
shield the less fortunate from the nega-
tive effects of the information age). For
example, in 1995, Gingrich went before
the House Ways and Means Cormnittee,
and during his testimony on various
issues before the committee, proposed
“a nutty idea that I am just throwing
out:” that poor families be given tax
credits to buy computers (never mind
that computer executives told Gingrich
that this was unrealistic). Great. They
may not have a job, but they can down-
load nude pics of Jenny McCarthy off
the intemet.

This belief, that technology is the
end—all to the problems of the world, is
more than a little naive. As we enter the
Information Age, economists are both-
ered by the fact that real wages and
worker productivity are apparently stag-
nating. Technology seems to be divid-
ing the world into the computer literate
haves and the have-nots, who have no
access to this technology.

Don’t get me wrong. Computers
can make our lives easier on many lev-
els. When I write on my computer,
instead of checking my work myself, I
can use my spell check to correct my
(many) mistakes. If I ﬁnd that I use the
word wonderful too much I can find
other ways to convey my opinion that
something is wonderful (“extraordi-
nary,” “great,” “impressive”) by using
the thesaurus.

However, many people (including
myself) have legitimate fears about
technology assuming a greater and
greater role in their lives. A sizeable
portion of society is afraid that comput-
ers and technology are dehumanizing
mankind. Even as we embrace the
march of technology, we must ask our-
selves if we are surrendering our
humanity in the process.

So back to the essential question; is
technology any good? I think so, but its
illusions tempt us to look at the
machines as our saviors instead of our-
selves. America’s greatest asset is our
people. Rather than give serious consid-
eration to Newt’s nutty idea that the
poor and children should have their
very own computers, we should be
looking for more fundamental solutions
like using technology to teach children
to read. The Information Age has the
potential to reap vast rewards, but is
also has the potential to horribly disap-
point us.

Michael Berquist would like to
remind everyone that there is no such
thing as a magical solution.

Gina Reynolds

 

